sec.p:
Other examples of elements that engaged and energized participants included:


A renewed emphasis on helping ex-offenders move towards better lives;



A focus on the importance of supervision as an active process in which individual offenders discover and exercise agency in seeking a better future;



The importance of developing both human and social capital, specifically capacities and skills, and opportunities respectively; 



Change supported by someone ‘believing in’ the offender, and the belief that the ‘someone’ can be the offender manager;



The Good Lives Model and support for a strengths based approach to service delivery;



A critique of the Coalition Green Paper ‘Breaking the Cycle’ which had been published only two days before the final seminar.
